Opening elevation: Niche: 900.67 m; Basin: 900.16 m.

Phase VII: Roman mid CE 2nd c. collapse and repairs. Aboveground canalization cut into the bedrock in the south and east. Installation of the low walls at the south ends of the East and West Walkways. Bench built along the south face of the South Corridor Wall. The floor of Room A is built up with purple sandstone bedding and low blocking wall. Room A is restructured as an animal shelter with tethering holes cut alongside the trough. Entrance to the Paradesios is blocked. A drain in the Forecourt is repaired and appointed with ceramic pipes for additional aboveground canalization.

Locus 34 is the semicircular niche with basin in the northeast of the bathroom. The niche is in the north of Locus 30, part of the original construction of that wall. At the base of the niche is a basin carved out of a single piece of limestone. The back of the niche has a vertical channel cut into it that curves over the top of the niche (width of 5 cm and depth of 3 cm). This channel would have held a pipe bringing water into the basin. The back of the niche is rather thin: 0.13 m in the south, 0.25 m in the southeast, and 0.16 m in the northeast. The basin itself is also semicircular, with a small depression in the back, and two holes in the northwest which get the accumulated water an outlet to flow out into the channel of the bathroom. The basin is cut to fit over the channel. Its exterior is finely diagonally dressed, and the interior is cleanly carved. This feature is thought to be a sink of sorts, with the water pouring over its top and falling down into the basin and finally flowing out into the channel. It is an elegant feature, and is central to the interpretation of this room as a bathroom. Before the room was filled with detritus, the niche was blocked (Locus 35). It is phased with the other features of the room to Stage 3.
Additions to the Complex, including the small reservoir, the bathroom and the anteroom.
